    <text>
        <body>
            <head>121. Memorandum From the President’s Assistant for National Security Affairs
                    (<persName corresp="rectQC2yY4UhXLeKu">Brzezinski</persName>) to President
                    <persName corresp="reccm3OnsdQpGeNR8">Carter</persName>
                <note n="1" place="foot" type="source" xml:id="d121fn1">Source: Carter Library,
                    National Security Affairs, Brzezinski Material, President’s Correspondence with
                    Foreign Leaders File, Box 13, <placeName corresp="recHYRQHh3kc1bSkH"
                        >Libya</placeName>: Secretary General <persName corresp="recQAFmups6ngiYAU"
                        >Mu’ammar Qadhafi</persName>, 3/77–1/80. Secret.</note>
            </head>
            <opener>
                <dateline rendition="#right">
                    <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1980-01-17"
                        >January 17, 1980</date>
                </dateline>
            </opener>
            <list type="subject">
                <head>SUBJECT</head>
                <item>Message to <persName corresp="recQAFmups6ngiYAU">Qadhafi</persName> (U)</item>
            </list>
            <p>You asked for a reassessment of the proposed message to <persName
                    corresp="recQAFmups6ngiYAU">Qadhafi</persName> in light of his comment
                suggesting that Americans take over the U.S. <pb facs="0313" n="292" xml:id="pg_292"
                /> Embassy in <placeName corresp="recHYRQHh3kc1bSkH">Libya</placeName> and make it
                into a “People’s Bureau” as the Libyans have done here. (S)</p>
            <p>My Staff has conferred with State on this issue. Jonathan Randall has told us that
                    <persName corresp="recQAFmups6ngiYAU">Qadhafi</persName>’s remark was made in a
                jocular manner, and it is our strong inclination not to pick up on it unless he
                makes it an issue. The best way to find out just what the Colonel has in mind is to
                arm our Charge with a serious message and then request a direct meeting. (S)</p>
            <p>A possible opening for our Charge may in fact occur tomorrow. A <orgName
                    corresp="recmLoDjMiF4yt3cM">Congressional</orgName> delegation is visiting
                Tripoli, and there is a real possibility that <persName corresp="recQAFmups6ngiYAU"
                    >Qadhafi</persName> will agree to meet with them. If he has the message in hand,
                    <persName corresp="recHqwjnAq6PNvMcs">Bill Eagleton</persName> would then be in
                a position to ask to remain for a one-on-one meeting with <persName
                    corresp="recQAFmups6ngiYAU">Qadhafi</persName> or to use the opportunity to let
                the Colonel know that such a meeting is desired. This will be a useful test of
                    <persName corresp="recQAFmups6ngiYAU">Qadhafi</persName>’s real interest in
                building a working relationship. (S)</p>
            <p>
                <hi rendition="simple_italic">RECOMMENDATION:</hi> That you approve the draft
                message at Tab A.<note n="2" place="foot" xml:id="d121fn2">Not attached. Beneath the
                    recommendation, <persName corresp="reccm3OnsdQpGeNR8">Carter</persName> wrote:
                    “OK, J.” In a January 17 note to NSC/S, <persName corresp="rectu0ilGsuuTnBLm"
                        >Sick</persName> wrote: “Approval of message relayed to Dept. of State by
                    phone.” (Carter Library, National Security Affairs, Brzezinski Material,
                    President’s Correspondence with Foreign Leaders File, Box 13, <placeName
                        corresp="recHYRQHh3kc1bSkH">Libya</placeName>: Secretary General <persName
                        corresp="recQAFmups6ngiYAU">Mu’ammar Qadhafi</persName>, 3/77–1/80) See <ref
                        target="#d123">Document 123</ref>.</note> (U)</p>
        </body>
